main_text: ğŸ… #pomegranate â¤ï¸ â€˜What is the structure and pharmacology of punicalagin?â€™ Thanks @amirhosein_firouzi_ for the great question! Punica granatum is a deciduous shrub native to the Middle East but is now grown around the world for its delicious fruit the pomegranate pictured above. Pomegranates contain a wide range of health-promoting compounds (swipe!) including a class of hydrolyzable ellagitannins polyphenols of which punicalagin pictured above is a member. Polyphenols are thought to protect plant tissues from ultraviolet radiation via the phenolic antioxidant mechanism (swipe!): hydroxyl groups oxidize and neutralize dangerous free radicals via quinone reduction. Punicalagin is an extensively hydroxylated polyphenol making it a potent antioxidant. In addition the glucose can be hydrolyzed and punicalagin can be metabolized into urolithins in the colon (swipe!) increasing the available oxidizing groups and total antioxidant capacity. Oxidative stress (swipe!) is one of the major pathological mechanisms involved in many types of diseases and conditions (swipe!). Often there is more information on clinical outcomes than mechanism of action because the money is in marketing and not in understanding. We donâ€™t exactly know how antioxidants can combat certain diseases but we do know that fruits and vegetables and plant-based diets are full of antioxidants! Do you like pomegranate? Who here loves pomegranates? Here is another amazing reason to devour them regularly! Pomegranates have been a symbol of fertility in Zoroastrian and other ancient cultures. ğŸ¤°No wonder - the structure of the pomegranate (and the look of it opened) has a strong resemblance to a female ovary.â â However itâ€™s not just the look of it - scientists have now discovered that pomegranates contain a form of female hormone oestrogen - called estrone - that is similar in function and structure to the one found in mammals. It is even believed that pomegranates are the richest source of it found in nature.â ğŸŒ±â â A 2004 study published in the Journal of Ethnopharmacology showed that pomegranates can help alleviate hormonal symptoms related to low oestrogen levels.â â Low oestrogen is often associated with issues in women such as low energy and fatigue acne abnormal facial and body hair as well as hot flushes and other symptoms of perimenopause.â â More good news is that unlike synthetic sources and some bioidentical sources of oestrogen - pomegranate does not have any of their potentially carcinogenic effects. âœŠ On the contrary - it acts as an adaptogen enhancing the levels of estrogen when it is low but blocking stronger estrogens if levels are excessive.â â According to GreenMedInfo:â â â€œIn an August 2011 study published in the Journal of Nutritional Biochemistry pomegranate extract was compared to the drugs Tamoxifen (T) and Estradiol (E) and was shown to prevent activity associated with estrogen-dependent cancer promotion without increasing the weight of the uterus a well known indicator of the potential carcinogenicity of (T) and (E)â€œ.â â How to enjoy it?â â¤ï¸ Eat the seeds whole (yep they can be eaten whole!)â â¤ï¸Drink it as a juice - but make sure itâ€™s pure and without the additivesâ â¤ï¸ For a powerful anti-ageing and antioxidant drink blend pomegranate juice with 1 tsp acai powderâ What are your favourite ways to eat a pomegranate?
